its mission largely as a stabilization and reconstruction deployment. However, as the campaign has evolved and the insurgency has proved to more resistant and capable, key operational imperatives have emerged, including military support to the civilian development effort, closer partnering with Afghan security forces, and greater military restraint. All participating militaries have adapted, to varying extents, to these campaign imperatives and pressures. This book analyzes these initiatives and their outcomes by focusing on the experiences of three groups of militaries: those of Britain, Canada, Denmark, the Netherlands, and the US, which have faced the most intense operational and strategic pressures; Germany, who's troops have faced the greatest political and cultural constraints; and the Afghan National Army (ANA) and the Taliban, who have been forced to adapt to a very different sets of circumstances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAfghan War, 2001- 0aAfghan War, 2001-. 0aMilitary policyvCase studies. 0aMilitary policyxCase studies. 0aOperational art (Military science)vCase studies. 0aOperational art (Military science)xCase studies. 0aTacticsvCase studies. 0aTacticsxCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aFarrell, Theo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOsinga, Frans, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRussell, James A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478676840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804786768423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804786768.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c